pull_request.title: cmd: add the upgrade command
pull_request.body:
This pull request introduces an "upgrade" command to the Hasura NDC Go connector CLI, automates migration of connector source code to the latest schema version, and standardizes path handling across the codebase. It also updates dependencies to their latest versions for improved stability and compatibility.

**New upgrade functionality:**

* Added a new `upgrade` command (`cmd/hasura-ndc-go/command/upgrade.go`) that patches `connector.go` to update the schema version and capability variable format, making migration to the latest NDC SDK easier.
* Integrated the `upgrade` command into the CLI entrypoint (`cmd/hasura-ndc-go/main.go`) and updated the command help text. [[1]](diffhunk://#diff-5b763412f7a0f1cc3fbc90b85cc40ccf515b6396dd69a01b952ec5a56500b862R20) [[2]](diffhunk://#diff-5b763412f7a0f1cc3fbc90b85cc40ccf515b6396dd69a01b952ec5a56500b862R55-R60)
* Updated the connector template to use the new `upgrade` command for configuration upgrades (`connector-metadata.yaml.tmpl`).
* Added unit tests for the upgrade patching logic (`cmd/hasura-ndc-go/command/upgrade_test.go`).

**Path handling improvements:**

* Replaced usage of `path` with `filepath` in all relevant Go files to ensure correct path handling on all operating systems. issue.title: Phase 3: Advanced Analytics Dashboard
issue.body:
## Overview
Create a comprehensive analytics dashboard providing deep insights into agent performance, cost optimization, team productivity, and system health metrics.

## Technical Requirements

### Core Features
- **Agent Performance Metrics**
  - Task completion rates
  - Response time distributions
  - Error rates and types
  - Resource utilization
  - Code quality metrics
  - Learning curve tracking

- **Cost Tracking & Optimization**
  - Real-time cost monitoring
  - Provider cost comparison
  - Budget vs actual tracking
  - Cost per task/feature
  - ROI calculations
  - Predictive cost modeling

- **Success Rate Analytics**
  - Task success/failure analysis
  - Retry patterns
  - Error categorization
  - Root cause analysis
  - Success factors correlation
  - Improvement recommendations

- **Team Productivity Insights**
  - Sprint velocity tracking
  - Burndown charts
  - Agent utilization rates
  - Bottleneck identification
  - Collaboration effectiveness
  - Time-to-value metrics

### Data Architecture
```typescript
interface AnalyticsEngine {
  collectors: DataCollector[];
  processors: DataProcessor[];
  storage: TimeSeriesDB;
  visualizations: DashboardWidget[];
  alerts: AlertRule[];
  reports: ReportGenerator[];
}

interface Metric {
  id: string;
  type: 'counter' | 'gauge' | 'histogram' | 'summary';
  dimensions: Map<string, string>;
  value: number;
  timestamp: Date;
  aggregations: AggregationType[];
}
```

### Implementation Requirements
1. **Data Collection Pipeline**
   - Event streaming (Kafka/Kinesis)
   - Metric aggregation service
   - Log analysis pipeline
   - Custom metric APIs
   - Data validation layer

2. **Storage & Processing**
   - Time-series database (InfluxDB/TimescaleDB)
   - Data warehouse (Snowflake/BigQuery)
   - Stream processing (Flink/Spark)
   - ML pipeline for predictions
   - Data retention policies

3. **Visualization Layer**
   - Real-time dashboards
   - Customizable widgets
   - Drill-down capabilities
   - Export functionality
   - Mobile-responsive design

## Dashboard Components
- **Executive Summary**
  - KPI scorecards
  - Trend indicators
  - Alert summary
  - Cost overview

- **Performance Dashboard**
  - Agent performance matrix
  - Response time heatmaps
  - Error rate trends
  - Resource utilization

- **Financial Dashboard**
  - Cost breakdown charts
  - Budget tracking
  - Provider comparison
  - Forecast models

- **Team Dashboard**
  - Sprint progress
  - Agent availability
  - Task distribution
  - Collaboration network

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Real-time data updates (<5s delay)
- [ ] Support for 100+ concurrent dashboard users
- [ ] 30-day data retention minimum
- [ ] Export to CSV/PDF/API
- [ ] Custom dashboard creation
- [ ] Alerting system with <1min latency
- [ ] Mobile app or responsive design
- [ ] API for programmatic access
- [ ] GDPR compliance for data handling

## Technical Stack
- Frontend: React + D3.js/Recharts
- Backend: Node.js + GraphQL
- Database: TimescaleDB + Redis
- Processing: Apache Kafka + Flink
- ML: Python + TensorFlow/PyTorch

## Priority
**P1** - Critical for optimization and insights

## Estimated Effort
5 weeks (3 developers + 1 data engineer)

## Technical Lead
@Maya_Rodriguez - Data processing expertise required

## Related Issues
- Depends on metrics collection infrastructure
- Integrates with cost tracking system
- Requires authentication/authorization

issue.title: Unifiedparser: Add support for config languages
issue.body:
# Feature request

The unifiedparser currently does not support config files (yml, json, etc..). Unfortunately these files often hide a lot of complexity as some projects move (too) much choice there and would currently be invisible.

## Description

As a auditor, I want even config files to be parsed, so I see large constructs in the map.

I can of course find these files with tokei as well. But since we are talking about a unified parser, it would be nice if it also contained config language parsing. 

## Acceptance criteria

The unified parser can parse:
- [ ] yml/yaml
- [ ] json
- [ ] toml
- [ ] xml
- [ ] .properties (the  .properties files that many java projects use)

The metrics it calculates are:
- [ ] LoC
- [ ] RLoC
- [ ] Comment lines

## Caveats

Complexity is rather impossible to define for config files. Maybe how deeply the files are nested? Or maybe complexity is always 0 or 1, but at least we notice large rloc. I have not checked what Sonar/Quodana do, but I would pick whatever they do.

comment.body: Closing this one as I think tokei is better suited to calculate all the myriad of config languages.

issue.title: Phase 3: Advanced Analytics Dashboard
issue.body:
## Overview
Create a comprehensive analytics dashboard providing deep insights into agent performance, cost optimization, team productivity, and system health metrics.

## Technical Requirements

### Core Features
- **Agent Performance Metrics**
  - Task completion rates
  - Response time distributions
  - Error rates and types
  - Resource utilization
  - Code quality metrics
  - Learning curve tracking

- **Cost Tracking & Optimization**
  - Real-time cost monitoring
  - Provider cost comparison
  - Budget vs actual tracking
  - Cost per task/feature
  - ROI calculations
  - Predictive cost modeling

- **Success Rate Analytics**
  - Task success/failure analysis
  - Retry patterns
  - Error categorization
  - Root cause analysis
  - Success factors correlation
  - Improvement recommendations

- **Team Productivity Insights**
  - Sprint velocity tracking
  - Burndown charts
  - Agent utilization rates
  - Bottleneck identification
  - Collaboration effectiveness
  - Time-to-value metrics

### Data Architecture
```typescript
interface AnalyticsEngine {
  collectors: DataCollector[];
  processors: DataProcessor[];
  storage: TimeSeriesDB;
  visualizations: DashboardWidget[];
  alerts: AlertRule[];
  reports: ReportGenerator[];
}

interface Metric {
  id: string;
  type: 'counter' | 'gauge' | 'histogram' | 'summary';
  dimensions: Map<string, string>;
  value: number;
  timestamp: Date;
  aggregations: AggregationType[];
}
```

### Implementation Requirements
1. **Data Collection Pipeline**
   - Event streaming (Kafka/Kinesis)
   - Metric aggregation service
   - Log analysis pipeline
   - Custom metric APIs
   - Data validation layer

2. **Storage & Processing**
   - Time-series database (InfluxDB/TimescaleDB)
   - Data warehouse (Snowflake/BigQuery)
   - Stream processing (Flink/Spark)
   - ML pipeline for predictions
   - Data retention policies

3. **Visualization Layer**
   - Real-time dashboards
   - Customizable widgets
   - Drill-down capabilities
   - Export functionality
   - Mobile-responsive design

## Dashboard Components
- **Executive Summary**
  - KPI scorecards
  - Trend indicators
  - Alert summary
  - Cost overview

- **Performance Dashboard**
  - Agent performance matrix
  - Response time heatmaps
  - Error rate trends
  - Resource utilization

- **Financial Dashboard**
  - Cost breakdown charts
  - Budget tracking
  - Provider comparison
  - Forecast models

- **Team Dashboard**
  - Sprint progress
  - Agent availability
  - Task distribution
  - Collaboration network

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Real-time data updates (<5s delay)
- [ ] Support for 100+ concurrent dashboard users
- [ ] 30-day data retention minimum
- [ ] Export to CSV/PDF/API
- [ ] Custom dashboard creation
- [ ] Alerting system with <1min latency
- [ ] Mobile app or responsive design
- [ ] API for programmatic access
- [ ] GDPR compliance for data handling

## Technical Stack
- Frontend: React + D3.js/Recharts
- Backend: Node.js + GraphQL
- Database: TimescaleDB + Redis
- Processing: Apache Kafka + Flink
- ML: Python + TensorFlow/PyTorch

## Priority
**P1** - Critical for optimization and insights

## Estimated Effort
5 weeks (3 developers + 1 data engineer)

## Technical Lead
@Maya_Rodriguez - Data processing expertise required

## Related Issues
- Depends on metrics collection infrastructure
- Integrates with cost tracking system
- Requires authentication/authorization

issue.title: Unifiedparser: Add support for config languages
issue.body:
# Feature request

The unifiedparser currently does not support config files (yml, json, etc..). Unfortunately these files often hide a lot of complexity as some projects move (too) much choice there and would currently be invisible.

## Description

As a auditor, I want even config files to be parsed, so I see large constructs in the map.

I can of course find these files with tokei as well. But since we are talking about a unified parser, it would be nice if it also contained config language parsing. 

## Acceptance criteria

The unified parser can parse:
- [ ] yml/yaml
- [ ] json
- [ ] toml
- [ ] xml
- [ ] .properties (the  .properties files that many java projects use)

The metrics it calculates are:
- [ ] LoC
- [ ] RLoC
- [ ] Comment lines

## Caveats

Complexity is rather impossible to define for config files. Maybe how deeply the files are nested? Or maybe complexity is always 0 or 1, but at least we notice large rloc. I have not checked what Sonar/Quodana do, but I would pick whatever they do.

comment.body: Closing this one as I think tokei is better suited to calculate all the myriad of config languages.
